DO $$
DECLARE
    v_course_id UUID;
    v_module_id UUID;
BEGIN
    SELECT id INTO v_course_id FROM courses WHERE title ILIKE '%Vibe Coding%' LIMIT 1;
    IF v_course_id IS NULL THEN RAISE EXCEPTION 'Vibe Coding course not found'; END IF;
    
    SELECT id INTO v_module_id FROM modules WHERE course_id = v_course_id AND ordering = 8 LIMIT 1;
    IF v_module_id IS NULL THEN RAISE EXCEPTION 'Module 8 not found'; END IF;
    
    RAISE NOTICE 'ðŸ“š Expanding Vibe Coding Module 8 (ALL 4 FINAL LESSONS)...';
    
    -- LESSON 25: Internal Tools
    UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="lesson-content"><h2>Internal Tools</h2><h3>Building Tools for Your Team</h3><p>One of the most practical applications of Vibe Coding is building internal toolsâ€”software that helps your team work more efficiently. These tools don''t need to be perfect or beautiful; they just need to solve real problems quickly. This lesson shows you how to identify opportunities and build internal tools with AI.</p><h3>Why Internal Tools?</h3><p>Internal tools are perfect for Vibe Coding because: Users are forgiving (they''re your colleagues). Requirements are flexible. Speed matters more than polish. You can iterate based on direct feedback. Impact is immediate and measurable. Lower risk than customer-facing products.</p><h3>Identifying Tool Opportunities</h3><h4>Look for Repetitive Tasks</h4><p>What does your team do repeatedly? Manual data entry. Copying between systems. Generating reports. Processing files. Sending routine emails. Updating spreadsheets.</p><p>Prompt: "I need a tool that automates [repetitive task]. It should [describe what it does]. Users are [describe users]."</p><h4>Look for Information Gaps</h4><p>What information is hard to find? Customer data scattered across systems. Project status unclear. Performance metrics not visible. Team availability unknown. Documentation outdated.</p><p>Prompt: "Build a dashboard that shows [information needed] by pulling data from [sources]."</p><h4>Look for Communication Friction</h4><p>Where does communication break down? Handoffs between teams. Status updates. Approval workflows. Feedback collection. Knowledge sharing.</p><p>Prompt: "Create a tool for [team] to [communicate/collaborate] on [task]."</p><h3>Common Internal Tool Types</h3><h4>1. Dashboards</h4><p>Real-time visibility into key metrics. Example: "Build a sales dashboard showing: Daily revenue, Top products, Sales by region, Team performance, Trend charts. Pull data from our CRM API."</p><h4>2. Admin Panels</h4><p>Manage data without touching the database. Example: "Create an admin panel to: View all users, Edit user details, Reset passwords, View activity logs, Export data to CSV."</p><h4>3. Data Processing Tools</h4><p>Transform or analyze data. Example: "Build a tool that: Accepts CSV upload, Validates data format, Processes records, Generates summary report, Exports results."</p><h4>4. Workflow Automation</h4><p>Automate multi-step processes. Example: "Create a tool for onboarding new employees: Send welcome email, Create accounts in all systems, Assign to team, Schedule orientation, Notify manager."</p><h4>5. Reporting Tools</h4><p>Generate regular reports automatically. Example: "Build a weekly report generator: Pull data from database, Calculate metrics, Generate charts, Format as PDF, Email to stakeholders."</p><h3>Building Internal Tools with AI</h3><h4>Step 1: Define the Problem</h4><p>Be specific about: Who will use it? What problem does it solve? What''s the current manual process? What''s the desired outcome?</p><h4>Step 2: Design the Simplest Solution</h4><p>Internal tools should be minimal: Single purpose. Simple UI. No unnecessary features. Fast to build. Easy to maintain.</p><h4>Step 3: Build Quickly</h4><p>Prompt: "Build a simple internal tool with: [describe functionality]. Tech stack: Next.js, Supabase, Tailwind. Simple, clean UI. No authentication needed (internal network only)."</p><h4>Step 4: Deploy and Test</h4><p>Get it in users'' hands fast: Deploy to internal server. Share with small group first. Gather feedback. Iterate quickly.</p><h4>Step 5: Iterate Based on Feedback</h4><p>Improve based on actual usage: "Users requested [feature]. Add it to the tool." "Users find [part] confusing. Simplify it." "Users want to export data. Add CSV export."</p><h3>Real-World Internal Tool Examples</h3><h4>Example 1: Customer Support Tool</h4><p>Problem: Support team manually looks up customer info across 3 systems. Solution: Unified customer lookup tool. Prompt: "Build a customer lookup tool: Search by email or ID. Show: Account details, Recent orders, Support tickets, Payment history. Pull from Stripe API, database, and support system API. Simple search interface."</p><h4>Example 2: Content Scheduler</h4><p>Problem: Marketing team uses spreadsheets to plan content. Solution: Visual content calendar. Prompt: "Create a content calendar tool: Drag-and-drop scheduling. View by week/month. Color-code by content type. Assign to team members. Export to CSV. Store in Supabase."</p><h4>Example 3: Expense Approver</h4><p>Problem: Expense approvals happen via email chains. Solution: Simple approval workflow. Prompt: "Build expense approval tool: Employees submit expenses (amount, category, receipt). Managers see pending approvals. Approve/reject with comments. Email notifications. Track approval history."</p><h4>Example 4: Team Availability</h4><p>Problem: Hard to know who''s available for meetings. Solution: Team availability dashboard. Prompt: "Create team availability tool: Show who''s in office/remote/off. Sync with Google Calendar. Show time zones. Quick meeting scheduler. Update your own status."</p><h3>Technical Considerations</h3><h4>Keep It Simple</h4><p>For internal tools: Use familiar tech stack. Avoid over-engineering. Skip unnecessary features. Prioritize speed over perfection. Don''t worry about scale (internal users are limited).</p><h4>Security for Internal Tools</h4><p>Even internal tools need security: Authentication (SSO if possible). Authorization (role-based access). Audit logs (who did what). Data validation. HTTPS only.</p><p>Prompt: "Add authentication using [your company''s SSO]. Only allow users with @company.com emails."</p><h4>Integration with Existing Systems</h4><p>Internal tools often need to connect to: CRM (Salesforce, HubSpot). Project management (Jira, Asana). Communication (Slack, Teams). Storage (Google Drive, S3). Databases (company database).</p><p>Prompt: "Integrate with Slack: Send notifications to #channel. Allow users to trigger actions from Slack. Post daily summaries."</p><h3>Measuring Success</h3><p>Track impact: Time saved (hours per week). Errors reduced. User adoption rate. Tasks automated. User satisfaction.</p><p>Simple metrics: "How much time did this save?" "How many people use it?" "What manual process did it replace?"</p><h3>Maintenance and Evolution</h3><h4>Plan for Maintenance</h4><p>Internal tools still need care: Monitor for errors. Update dependencies. Fix bugs. Add requested features. Archive when no longer needed.</p><h4>Documentation</h4><p>Document for your team: How to use it. How it works (for future maintainers). API keys and credentials. Deployment process. Common issues and fixes.</p><h4>Handoff Strategy</h4><p>If you leave: Document everything. Train someone else. Make code readable. Avoid complex dependencies. Consider long-term ownership.</p><h3>Common Pitfalls</h3><p><strong>Pitfall 1: Over-Engineering</strong><br>Don''t build enterprise software for 5 users. Keep it simple.</p><p><strong>Pitfall 2: Building Without User Input</strong><br>Talk to users before building. Validate the problem exists.</p><p><strong>Pitfall 3: Ignoring Security</strong><br>Even internal tools handle sensitive data. Implement basic security.</p><p><strong>Pitfall 4: No Maintenance Plan</strong><br>Tools break. Plan for ongoing maintenance.</p><h3>Getting Started</h3><p>Your first internal tool: Identify one painful manual process. Talk to the people doing it. Design the simplest solution. Build it in a day with AI. Deploy and gather feedback. Iterate based on usage.</p><h3>Key Takeaways</h3><ul><li>Internal tools are <strong>perfect for Vibe Coding</strong>: fast, forgiving, high impact</li><li>Look for opportunities in <strong>repetitive tasks, information gaps, communication friction</strong></li><li>Common types: <strong>dashboards, admin panels, data processors, workflow automation</strong></li><li>Keep it <strong>simple</strong>: single purpose, minimal UI, fast to build</li><li>Build <strong>quickly</strong>, deploy, gather feedback, iterate</li><li>Don''t over-engineerâ€”<strong>good enough is good enough</strong> for internal tools</li><li>Measure <strong>impact</strong>: time saved, errors reduced, adoption rate</li><li>Plan for <strong>maintenance and handoff</strong></li></ul><p>In the next lesson, we''ll explore using Vibe Coding for client work and freelancing.</p></div>'
    WHERE module_id = v_module_id AND ordering = 1;
    RAISE NOTICE 'âœ… Lesson 25 Complete';
    
    -- LESSON 26: Client Work
    UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="lesson-content"><h2>Client Work</h2><h3>Delivering Value with Vibe Coding</h3><p>Vibe Coding opens new opportunities for client work and freelancing. You can deliver projects faster, take on more clients, and provide more value. This lesson teaches you how to use AI effectively in client work while maintaining quality, managing expectations, and building a sustainable practice.</p><h3>The Vibe Coding Advantage for Freelancers</h3><p>AI gives you superpowers: Deliver projects 3-5x faster. Take on more clients simultaneously. Offer competitive pricing. Provide quick iterations. Handle diverse tech stacks. Scale your practice without hiring.</p><h3>Types of Client Work</h3><h4>1. MVPs and Prototypes</h4><p>Perfect for Vibe Coding. Client needs: Validate business idea quickly. Show to investors. Test with users. Minimal viable features.</p><p>Your approach: Use Bolt.new or Lovable for speed. Focus on core functionality. Beautiful but simple design. Deploy quickly. Iterate based on feedback.</p><p>Pricing: $2,000-$10,000 for 1-2 week projects.</p><h4>2. Landing Pages and Marketing Sites</h4><p>High demand, fast delivery. Client needs: Professional web presence. Lead generation. Product showcase. SEO optimization.</p><p>Your approach: Use v0 for components. Tailwind for styling. Next.js for performance. Integrate with email/CRM. Deploy to Vercel.</p><p>Pricing: $1,000-$5,000 per site.</p><h4>3. Internal Tools and Dashboards</h4><p>Businesses always need these. Client needs: Automate manual processes. Visualize data. Improve team efficiency. Custom workflows.</p><p>Your approach: Understand their process. Build simple, focused tools. Integrate with existing systems. Train their team.</p><p>Pricing: $3,000-$15,000 depending on complexity.</p><h4>4. API Integrations</h4><p>Connect systems together. Client needs: Sync data between platforms. Automate workflows. Centralize information. Reduce manual work.</p><p>Your approach: Map data flows. Use Zapier/n8n for simple cases. Build custom integrations for complex needs. Handle errors gracefully.</p><p>Pricing: $1,500-$8,000 per integration.</p><h4>5. Maintenance and Updates</h4><p>Ongoing revenue. Client needs: Keep site updated. Fix bugs. Add features. Security updates. Performance optimization.</p><p>Your approach: Monthly retainer. Quick turnaround with AI. Proactive improvements. Regular communication.</p><p>Pricing: $500-$3,000/month retainer.</p><h3>The Client Work Process</h3><h4>Step 1: Discovery and Scoping</h4><p>Understand the project: What problem are they solving? Who are the users? What''s the desired outcome? What''s the timeline? What''s the budget?</p><p>Use AI to help: "I''m scoping a project for [client]. They need [description]. What questions should I ask? What potential challenges should I consider?"</p><h4>Step 2: Proposal and Pricing</h4><p>Create clear proposals: Project scope (what''s included). Timeline and milestones. Deliverables. Pricing (fixed or hourly). Terms and conditions.</p><p>Pricing with AI: Estimate time without AI. Divide by 3-5 (AI speedup). Add buffer for revisions. Price based on value, not just time.</p><h4>Step 3: Design and Planning</h4><p>Before coding: Create wireframes or mockups. Get client approval on design. Plan technical architecture. Set up project infrastructure.</p><p>Use AI: "Create a technical plan for [project]. Include: Tech stack recommendations, Database schema, API structure, Deployment strategy."</p><h4>Step 4: Development</h4><p>Build with AI: Use appropriate tools for the project. Build modularly. Test as you go. Commit to version control regularly. Document important decisions.</p><h4>Step 5: Client Communication</h4><p>Keep clients informed: Weekly progress updates. Demo working features. Ask for feedback early. Manage expectations. Be transparent about challenges.</p><h4>Step 6: Delivery and Handoff</h4><p>Professional delivery: Deploy to production. Provide documentation. Train the client. Transfer ownership. Offer support period.</p><h3>Managing Client Expectations</h3><h4>Be Transparent About AI</h4><p>Should you tell clients you use AI? Opinions vary: Some freelancers are transparent. Others focus on results, not methods. Consider your client and project.</p><p>If asked: "I use modern development tools including AI assistance to deliver high-quality work efficiently. This allows me to offer competitive pricing and faster delivery."</p><h4>Set Realistic Timelines</h4><p>Even with AI: Account for revisions. Include buffer time. Consider client feedback cycles. Plan for unexpected issues.</p><h4>Define Scope Clearly</h4><p>Prevent scope creep: List what''s included. List what''s not included. Charge for additional requests. Use change request process.</p><h3>Quality Assurance for Client Work</h3><h4>Review All AI Code</h4><p>Never deliver unreviewed AI code: Understand what it does. Test thoroughly. Check for security issues. Optimize if needed. Add comments.</p><h4>Testing Checklist</h4><p>Before delivery: All features work as specified. Responsive on mobile/tablet/desktop. Cross-browser compatibility. No console errors. Performance is acceptable. Security best practices followed. Accessibility basics covered.</p><h4>Use Verification Prompts</h4><p>"Review this code for client delivery: Security vulnerabilities. Performance issues. Code quality. Best practices. Potential bugs."</p><h3>Building Long-Term Client Relationships</h3><h4>Exceed Expectations</h4><p>Go beyond the contract: Suggest improvements. Fix small issues without charging. Provide helpful resources. Be responsive. Deliver early when possible.</p><h4>Offer Ongoing Value</h4><p>After project completion: Monthly maintenance retainers. Feature additions. Performance optimization. Security updates. Strategic consulting.</p><h4>Ask for Referrals</h4><p>Happy clients refer others: Ask at project completion. Make it easy (provide template). Offer referral incentive. Stay in touch.</p><h3>Pricing Strategies</h3><h4>Value-Based Pricing</h4><p>Price based on client value, not your time: What''s it worth to them? How much time/money does it save? What revenue does it enable? Price accordingly.</p><h4>Package Pricing</h4><p>Offer tiered packages: Basic: $X (core features). Standard: $Y (+ additional features). Premium: $Z (+ custom features, priority support).</p><h4>Retainer Model</h4><p>Predictable income: Monthly hours allocation. Priority support. Ongoing improvements. Relationship building.</p><h3>Common Client Work Challenges</h3><p><strong>Challenge:</strong> Client wants endless revisions.<br><strong>Solution:</strong> Include specific revision count in contract. Charge for additional revisions. Set clear approval process.</p><p><strong>Challenge:</strong> Client doesn''t know what they want.<br><strong>Solution:</strong> Guide them with questions. Show examples. Build prototype to clarify. Charge for discovery phase.</p><p><strong>Challenge:</strong> Client compares your speed to traditional developers.<br><strong>Solution:</strong> Focus on value and results. Emphasize quality and testing. Explain your efficient process. Price based on value, not hours.</p><p><strong>Challenge:</strong> Scope keeps expanding.<br><strong>Solution:</strong> Document original scope. Use change request process. Charge for additions. Be firm but professional.</p><h3>Building Your Practice</h3><h4>Finding Clients</h4><p>Where to find work: Upwork, Fiverr (start here). LinkedIn (build presence). Referrals (best source). Local businesses (underserved). Your network (tell everyone).</p><h4>Portfolio</h4><p>Showcase your work: 3-5 strong projects. Live demos (not just screenshots). Case studies (problem, solution, results). Testimonials. GitHub profile.</p><h4>Specialization</h4><p>Consider focusing on: Industry (healthcare, real estate, e-commerce). Project type (MVPs, landing pages, dashboards). Technology (Next.js, Supabase, specific platforms). Problem (automation, integrations, data visualization).</p><h3>Legal and Business Considerations</h3><p>Protect yourself: Use contracts (every project). Define IP ownership. Include payment terms. Set cancellation policy. Have liability limits. Consider LLC formation. Get insurance (E&O).</p><h3>Scaling Your Practice</h3><p>As you grow: Raise your rates. Be more selective. Build systems and templates. Outsource admin work. Consider partnerships. Create productized services.</p><h3>Key Takeaways</h3><ul><li>Vibe Coding enables <strong>faster delivery and competitive pricing</strong></li><li>Best opportunities: <strong>MVPs, landing pages, internal tools, integrations</strong></li><li>Follow a <strong>professional process</strong>: discovery, proposal, development, delivery</li><li>Manage expectations: <strong>clear scope, realistic timelines, transparent communication</strong></li><li><strong>Always review AI code</strong> before client delivery</li><li>Build <strong>long-term relationships</strong> through quality and value</li><li>Price based on <strong>value, not just time</strong></li><li>Protect yourself with <strong>contracts and clear terms</strong></li></ul><p>In the next lesson, we''ll explore the future of software development and where Vibe Coding is heading.</p></div>'
    WHERE module_id = v_module_id AND ordering = 2;
    RAISE NOTICE 'âœ… Lesson 26 Complete';
    
    RAISE NOTICE 'ðŸŽ‰ Module 8 Lessons 1-2 Complete! (2 more to go)';
    
END $$;
